@flexiarg writing-coherence/hedged-lift
@title Commit, Defer Properly, or Cut
@keywords hedging, strong-claim, softener, beyond-the-scope, defer, forward-pointer
@audience paper authors, reviewers
@tone technical
@style pattern
@references [writing-coherence/throat-clearing-close writing-coherence/scope-mush]

! conclusion: A strong sentence immediately softened by a disclaimer — "though beyond the scope of this paper", "though further work is needed", "though we do not defend this claim here" — asks the reader to both accept the lift and exempt the writer from defending it.  The hedge does rhetorical work the argument has not done.  Either commit and defend, or defer properly with a forward pointer the reader can chase, or cut.
  + context: Hedging is useful.  A hedge that names a precise scope limit is a service to the reader.  A hedge that gestures vaguely at limits ("though beyond the scope", "more research is needed", "though nuance exists") is authorial risk management masquerading as scholarly care.  The same sentence cannot both lift and retreat.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: claim strength ↔ authorial safety.
    Real: every claim exposes the writer to challenge; the stronger the claim, the larger the exposure.  Hedges reduce exposure but also reduce what the reader can take away.
    Irreducible: a sentence cannot maximise both strength and safety; the hedge is the visible negotiation.
    Active: the pull recurs at every strong-claim sentence, particularly in conclusion paragraphs and abstracts.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Commit and defend: keep the strong sentence; use the next sentence to give the reader the argument or evidence behind it.  Pay what the lift promised.
    (2) Defer properly: keep the strong sentence; replace the vague hedge with a forward pointer the reader can follow — "(see §5 for the structural argument)", "(this is the subject of a forthcoming paper, Corneli in preparation)".  The deferral is now a service, not an escape.
    (3) Cut: if the claim cannot be defended now and cannot be properly deferred, it does not belong in the text.  Remove the sentence.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: every strong claim in the draft is either followed by a defence, accompanied by a precise forward pointer, or removed.  Failing when: strong claims are followed by vague acknowledgements of limits ("though this is complex", "though nuance exists") that neither defend nor defer.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Beyond-the-scope: "important, though beyond the scope of this paper".
    - Future-work as escape: "we leave a full treatment to future work" with no indication of what the treatment would involve.
    - Complexity plea: "the situation is of course more complex than this".
    - Obligatory nuance: "while acknowledging important nuances..." followed by none.
